About this hotel

    TL;DR Beyond beautiful and the staff is beyond helpful.
    We stayed at La Sultana for our honeymoon in a junior suite. The room was …
    TL;DR Beyond beautiful and the staff is beyond helpful.
    We stayed at La Sultana for our honeymoon in a junior suite. The room was amazing. The bathroom matches the extraordinary beauty of the rest of the hotel, with a large bath, shower, dual sinks and seperate vanity.
    The pool is just awe-some. Not in the slang sense, but it's beauty brings a sense of awe not seen in modern construction. Somehow, the small pool courtyard even tops its beauty, though maybe not it's poolside feel.
    Food was fantastic. I would recommend the Morrocain sampler. We had it our first night, and nothing could have brought in a better welcome to Merakesh. Lunch is great as well, just note that fries are basically homemade chips (for us travellers, crisps for UK) though very delicious.
    We did not have alcoholic drinks anywhere else during our stay, but prices were very reasonable for a fine resort like this. A bottle of Rosé at the pool is heavenly, and any medallion (a Morrocain wine) at the rooftop at night was our night cap.
    It's in the old city, literally adjacent to the Saadian tombs, and just a short walk from the bahia and badi palaces. Also a short walk to the Jamaa El F'na square and souks.
    We had the luxury of the Royal Hammam at the spa. The spa is perhaps more beautiful than the hotel itself. The Hammam was the best clean feeling I have ever had, topping a old water bath of a traditional native America sweat lodge in the southwest of the USA. It topped it by a lot. The massage that followed was fantastic, and dont be concerned with a weak massage like other reviews have mentioned. I typically like mine k. The higher pressure side, and had to ask for lower pressure. I actually fell asleep in the chair afterwards. They let you rest and are not rushed to leave after your massage, a first for me.
    Last and most important is the staff. They are beyond accommodating and sincere in wanting you to enjoy tour experience to the fullest. Every single person I have interacted with has been extraordinarily respectful, accomodating and helpful. Maybe we weren't used to this level of service, but it was almost too helpful.
    We can't wait to come back or try the coastal la sultana. Hopefully they can match this service.
    Ps. Make sure to take a day trip to essaouira. It's an awesome town.

    FOOD POISONING!
    We went for lunch at La Sultana on Friday 4th November. If I could give 0 stars, I would. The building is incredible, but that's where the positives end. We spent 900 dirham on 2 mains and half a bottle of wine, which is very dear considering the service and quality of food. I tried the camel burger/sandwich and have food poisoning - I've been up all night with my head in the toilet. As I was eating the meal, I just had a feeling something wasn't quite right but I convinced myself everything was OK due to the reputation of the establishment. Moral of the story - trust your gut. There are far more cost effective, better quality, high-end restaurants in Marrakech than this one.

    Kasbah

    Busy Kasbah is home to old-world souks, street-food vendors selling grilled meats and basara (bean soup), and hip cafes. Its imposing medina gate, the 12th-century, horseshoe-shaped Bab Agnaou, is decorated with Quranic inscriptions. Near Moulay El-Yazid Mosque, the Saadian Tombs are royal graves in chambers with ornate mosaic tiling and stucco. Close by, the huge, ruined El-Badii Palace dates to the 16th century.

    Great location overall for sightseeing, recreation, dining, and getting around

    About this hotel

    A minute's walk from the Saadian Tombs, this sophisticated, luxury riad is also a 14-minute walk from Jemaa el-Fnaa square. …

    The luxe, elegant rooms feature complimentary Wi-Fi and non-alcoholic minibars, plus satellite TV and iPod docks. Suites add private balconies. An upgraded suite features a whirlpool tub, a terrace, and a living room with a fireplace. Room service is offered 24/7.

    Amenities include an outdoor heated pool, a sundeck, and a restaurant with a seasonal rooftop terrace. There's a pool table, a library and a cocktail lounge, as well as a gym, and a spa with open-air massage rooms. Breakfast and cooking classes are available.
